{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496507"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:48:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:48:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1372"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1372"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.07,0.02,0.03,0.82]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1372"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109046"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1372"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1372"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91412"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"175"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2115"},{"type":"tags","id":"3467"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5480"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6998"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12387"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12949"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15138"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15186"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37088"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42297"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44577"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109046"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with abdominal pain. He is diagnosed with diverticulitis, which responds well to conservative treatment. As part of the investigations, a contrast-enhanced CT scan of the abdomen is performed (Image). This confirms the diagnosis of diverticulitis and reveals an incidental finding of a 5.6 cm infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysm. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. The abdomen is soft and non-tender.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management of the aortic aneurysm?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Surveillance ultrasound in six months","Surveillance CT in six months","Surveillance CT in 12 months","Risk factor modification and GP review","Prompt vascular surgical opinion"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an incidentally discovered infrarenal abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) measuring 5.6 cm in maximal anterior-posterior (AP) diameter. The current threshold size for elective repair of a fusiform, degenerative AAA is 55 mm in men and 50 mm in women. At this threshold size, the annual risk of rupture is between 1-11%.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E prompt vascular surgical opinion\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management for this patient. Given that his AAA is above the threshold size for men (5.5 cm), he should be referred to a vascular surgical unit for consideration of elective repair. The decision about the timing and method of repair will be based on a balance between the risk of operative mortality and the risk of aneurysm rupture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe options for treatment of AAA include open repair or endovascular aneurysm repair (EVAR). The choice of treatment will depend on patient factors including fitness for surgery and AAA anatomy. Some AAAs are not suitable for standard EVARs and may require more complex endovascular interventions or an open repair.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurveillance ultrasound in six months\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for AAAs measuring 5.0-5.4 cm, but this patient\u0027s AAA is already above the threshold for intervention. Similarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Esurveillance CT in six or 12 months\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate for an AAA of this size. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERisk factor modification and GP review\u003C/strong\u003E alone is insufficient for an AAA of this size. While risk factor modification (including antiplatelet therapy, statin therapy, blood pressure control, and management of diabetes if present) is important, it should be implemented alongside referral for surgical evaluation, not as a standalone management plan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is worth noting that approximately 95% of abdominal aortic aneurysms are found incidentally, as in this case. The management approach differs based on the size of the AAA, with increasing frequency of follow-up scans recommended for larger subthreshold AAAs. However, once the threshold size is reached, as in this case, referral for surgical evaluation is indicated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Any abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) of \u003E40 mm requires at least regular imaging surveillance.","Surgical opinion is required for patients with asymptomatic AAA \u003E55 mm in men and \u003E50 mm in women.","The decision for AAA repair is based on balancing the risk of operative mortality against the risk of aneurysm rupture."],"references":["Wanhainen A, Verzini F, Van Herzeele I, Allaire E, Bown M, Cohnert T. Editor\u0027s Choice - European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS) 2019 Clinical Practice Guidelines on the Management of Abdominal Aorto-iliac Artery Aneurysms. Eur J Vasc Endovasc Surg. 2019 Jan;57(1):8-93. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30528142/","Cronenwett JL, Johnston KW. Rutherford\u0027s vascular surgery E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences. 2014.","McCleary AJ, Mahomed A. UK small aneurysms trial. The Lancet. 1999;353(9150):408. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(05)74980-1/fulltext","Lederle FA, Johnson GR, Wilson SE, Chute EP, Hye RJ, Makaroun MS, et al. The aneurysm detection and management study screening program: validation cohort and final results. Aneurysm Detection and Management Veterans Affairs Cooperative Study Investigators. Arch Intern Med. 2000;160(10):1425-30. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10826454/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91412"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1372"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17094"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17094"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f95ef24b-f018-475d-8f8f-0d6547ed7b98.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f95ef24b-f018-475d-8f8f-0d6547ed7b98.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":410,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91412"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-16T15:44:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-16T15:44:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1372"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109046"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"